{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17502559","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17502559"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T10:46:43+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T10:46:43+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1876"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1876","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1876"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.08,0.2,0.38,0.2,0.14]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1876"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"85136"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1876","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1876"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1876"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"69352"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"30"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"853"},{"type":"tags","id":"1139"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"8182"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8316"},{"type":"contributions","id":"28926"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"85136","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/85136"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 70-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department after several episodes of upper abdominal pain over the last three weeks. The episodes resolve without intervention but appear to be increasing in severity. He has not had any alteration to his bowel habit. His medical history includes hypertension treated with indapamide, and gallstones.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination his abdomen is distended but soft with normal bowel sounds. His cardiorespiratory examination is unremarkable.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHis blood tests show:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHaemoglobin 140 g/L (120-175)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhite cell count 4 x10^9/L (2-11)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPlatelets 200 x10^9/L (150-500)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAlkaline phosphatase 27 U/L (\u0026lt;35)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EGamma-glutamyl transferase 30 U/L (\u0026lt;100)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAspartate aminotransferase 21 U/L (\u0026lt;35)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAlanine aminotransferase 23 U/L (\u0026lt;35)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ELipase negative\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUrine dipstick negative\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHe has normal electrolytes and renal function.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA CT abdomen is performed (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely explanation for the changes seen on the scan?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Cholecystitis","Large bowel obstruction","Gallstone ileus","Intestinal ischaemia","Previous endoscopic sphincterotomy"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis image shows that air is visible in the biliary tree. The commonest explanation for this (incidental) finding is a \u003Cstrong\u003Eprevious endoscopic retrograde cholangiopancreatography (ERCP)\u003C/strong\u003E, where a \u003Cstrong\u003Esphincterotomy\u003C/strong\u003E is commonly performed as part of the procedure - particularly to help with stone extraction. Once the sphincter has been divided, it is easy for air from the digestive tract to get up into the biliary tree. This is of no pathological significance.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIncidental findings on imaging are relatively common and may be found in up to 50% of abdominal CT scans in adults. With such frequency and the understanding that most of these \u0027incidentalomas\u0027 are of no clinical significance, it is important that they are identified and recognised as such.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECholecystitis\u003C/strong\u003E is the inflammation of the gallbladder, most commonly due to a gallstone obstructing the gallbladder outlet. On CT, it usually presents with gallbladder distention and wall thickening, along with stones if they are present and/or the cause of the inflammation. This CT does not show any of these features.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Elarge bowel obstruction\u003C/strong\u003E would usually present with clearly defined colonic dilation proximal to the obstruction site. This patient\u0027s CT does not show colonic dilation nor a clear transition point.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Egallstone ileus\u003C/strong\u003E would show a radiodense opacity usually at the ileocaecal junction. It is a relatively uncommon presentation and can often be diagnosed on plain abdominal X-ray.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntestinal ischaemia\u003C/strong\u003E has various imaging findings depending on the stage and severity of the ischaemia. Necrosis of the bowel wall is usually followed by bacterial proliferation and resultant gas production within the gut wall - i.e. pneumatosis intestinalis. Perforation, a significant consequence of ischaemia, can be visualised as a pneumoperitoneum (air within the abdominal cavity). This patient has none of these findings. If this image showed air in the portal system from intestinal ischaemia, he would be very sick and have obvious abdominal signs of peritonitis.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Air in the biliary tree can be both benign and pathological"],"references":["Gaillard F, Jones J, Bell D, et al. Pneumobilia. Reference article, Radiopaedia.org (Accessed on 20 Feb 2023) https://doi.org/10.53347/rID-1900","Radswiki T, Murphy A, Omar Carrim Y, et al. Acute cholecystitis. Reference article, Radiopaedia.org (Accessed on 21 Feb 2023) https://doi.org/10.53347/rID-12084","Gaillard F, Chieng R, Hacking C, et al. Mesenteric ischemia. Reference article, Radiopaedia.org (Accessed on 20 Feb 2023) https://doi.org/10.53347/rID-1514"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"69352"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1876"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"19303"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"19303","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/19303"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/1b086860-aeb5-445a-ad4a-c078da7e5f70.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/1b086860-aeb5-445a-ad4a-c078da7e5f70.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":525,"height":600}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"69352","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/69352"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-02-15T09:20:40+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-02-15T09:21:25+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1876"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"85136"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"30","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/30"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udff4\u200d\u2620\ufe0f","name":"Radiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-15T15:37:12+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationshi